{"parse":{"title":"yes","pageid":3207,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|yés|yɛ́s|þes}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''Yes'''kwa}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp|+ and no}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|yes}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġīese|t=by all means, of course, yes}}, derived from the same root as {{m|en|yea}}. Compare {{cog|fo|júsá|t=yes, indeed, certainly}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/jɛs/}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-yes.ogg|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Naomi Persephone Amethyst (NaomiAmethyst)-yes.wav|a=GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-yes.ogg|a=US}}\n** {{audio|en|En-nz-yes.ogg|a=NZ|IPA=[jes]}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛs|s=1}}\n\n===Particle===\n{{en-head|pcl}}\n\n# {{non-gloss|Used to show [[agree]]ment or acceptance.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Yes''', you are correct.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Yes''', you may go play outside now.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Yes''', sir, we have your package right here.}}\n#* '''2016''', [https://web.archive.org/web/20171030003034/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/lets-learn-english-lesson-8-are-you-busy/3253185.html VOA Learning English] (public domain)\n#*: Hi, Jonathan. Are you busy? &mdash; '''Yes''', I’m busy.\n# {{non-gloss|Used to indicate ''disagreement'' or ''dissent'' in reply to a negative statement.}}\n#: {{ux|en|It was not my fault we lost the race.<br>Oh, '''yes''', it was!}}\n# {{lb|en|humorous}} {{n-g|Answer to a question presuming one answer when all answers are correct.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Do you like cake, or pie?<br>'''Yes'''.}}\n#: {{rfquote-sense|en}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* In Old and Middle English, ''yes'' was a more forceful affirmative than {{m|en|yea}}.\n* An example of '''yes''' used to disagree with a statement: the questions \"You don’t want it, do you?\" and \"Don’t you want it?\" are answered by \"yes\" if the respondent ''does'' want the item, and \"no\" if not. Many languages use a specific word for this purpose; see translation table below.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* Dialect or archaic forms: [[arr]], [[ay]], [[aye]], [[yea]], [[yassuh]]\n* Nautical, military, telecommunications: [[affirmative]]\n* Colloquial or slang forms: [[ya]], [[yah]], [[yeah]], <!--links to pronoun only: [[ye]], -->[[yeh]], [[yep]], [[yeppers]], [[yup]], [[yuppers]], [[yus]], [[ahuh]], [[mhm]], [[uh huh]], [[ye-es]]\n* See also: [[Thesaurus:yes]]\n\n====Antonyms====\n* Standard form: [[no]]\n* Nautical, military, telecommunications: [[negative]]\n* Dialect or archaic forms: [[nay]]\n* Colloquial or slang forms: [[ixnay]], [[nah]], [[naw]], [[nope]]\n* See also: [[Thesaurus:no]]\n\n====Coordinate terms====\n* {{sense|expression of agreement or acceptance}} {{l|en|nod}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|en\n|say yes\n|very yes\n|yes and\n|yes and amen\n|yes and no\n|yes-brainer\n|yes-huh\n|yes ma'am\n|yes-man\n|yesman,yes man\n|[[Appendix:Terms with no English equivalent/yes-no|yes-no]]\n|yes-no question,yes-or-no question\n|yessuh\n|yessum\n|yes, Virginia\n|yes woman\n}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{multitrans|data=\n{{trans-top|word used to indicate agreement or acceptance}}\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|ааи}},  {{t|ab|аиеи}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|ja}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|po}}\n* Aleut: {{t|ale|aang}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|эйе}}\n* Alutiiq: {{t|ems|aa'a}}\n* American Sign Language: {{t|ase|S@Side Nod}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|አዎን}}\n* Apache:\n*: Western Apache: {{t|apw|au}},  {{t|apw|haʼah}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|نَعَم}},  {{t+|ar|أَجَل}},  {{t+|ar|إِي}}\n*: Algerian Arabic: {{t|arq|ايه}},  {{t|arq|هيه}},  {{t|arq|واه}}\n*: Cypriot Arabic: {{t|acy|ye}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|أَيْوَة|tr=ʔaywa}},  {{t|arz|ايوه|tr=ʔaywa}},  {{t|arz|اه|tr=ā}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|إيوه|tr=īwa}},  {{t|acw|نَعَم|tr=naʕam}} {{qualifier|in response to call}}\n*: Iraqi Arabic: {{t|acm|إي|tr=ī}}\n*: North Levantine Arabic: {{t|apc|اِيه|tr=ē}},  {{t|ajp|نعم|tr=naʔam}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{t|ajp|آه|tr=ʔā}},  {{t|ajp|أيوه|tr=ʔaywa}},  {{t|ajp|نعم|tr=naʔam}}\n* Aragonese: {{t|an|sí}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Hebrew script: {{t|arc|אין|tr=’ēn}}\n*: Syriac: {{t|arc|ܐܝܢ|tr=’ēn}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|այո}} {{qualifier|polite}},  {{t+|hy|հա}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|ie}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|অঁ}},  {{t|as|হয়}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|sí}}\n* Aymara: {{t+|ay|jisa}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|bəli}},  {{t+|az|hə}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|эйе}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|bai}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|так}},  {{t|be|да}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|হ্যাঁ}},  {{t+|bn|জি}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|हँ}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{t+|bcl|iyo}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|ya}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|да}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ဟုတ်ကဲ့}},  {{t+|my|အင်း}},  {{t+|my|အေး}} {{qualifier|among equals or to people of lower status}}\n* Burushaski: {{t|bsk|awá}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{t|rue|айно}},  {{t|rue|так}},  {{t|rue|йо}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|sí}}\n* Central Atlas Tamazight: {{t|tzm|ⵢⴰⵀ}}\n* Chamicuro: {{t|ccc|eje}}\n* Chechen: {{t|ce|хӏаъ}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎥᎥ}}\n* Chichewa: {{t|ny|inde}}\n* Chickasaw: {{t|cic|i̠i}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|係|tr=hai6}},  {{t+|yue|唔|tr=m4}},  {{t|yue|嗯|tr=ng2}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|好|tr=hó}},  {{t+|nan-hbl|是|tr=sī / sǐ}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|是|tr=shì}},  {{t+|cmn|對|tr=duì}},  {{t+|cmn|啊|tr=à}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, (repeating the verb/attribute used in the question to mean \"yes\" 你'''知道'''吗？ '''知道''')\n* Choctaw: {{t|cho|a̱}}\n* Comanche: {{t|com|haa}}\n* Coptic: {{t|cop|ⲁϩⲁ}},  {{t|cop|ⲥⲉ}}\n* Corsican: {{t|co|iè}},  {{t|co|sì}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|ano}},  {{t+|cs|jo}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|ja}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|ja}}\n* Egyptian: {{t-egy|tjw|h=ti-W-A2}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|jes}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|jah}},  {{t+|et|jaa}}\n* Faroese: {{t+|fo|ja}}\n* Fijian: {{t+|fj|io}}\n* Finnish: {{q|{{w|echo answer}} - use the verb}},  {{t+|fi|kyllä}} {{qualifier|literary}},  {{t+|fi|joo}} {{qualifier|colloquial}},